<br>
Derek French - Assistant Producer - NWN<br>
<br>
<br>
Downloading Modules <br>
Quote: RPG Junkie wrote: Will it automatically download it into like a &quot;modules&quot; directory under NWN or will it be like in Quake 3 and UT to where you manually install it ????<br>
<br>
In Windows and the strict sense of your question, it will be a manual download and install. This is because we cannot control where your web browser's default download directory. Some times its your desktop, sometimes its &quot;My Documents&quot;, etc. But, we are planning to make the downloads from our Community site come with a mini-installer that will extract the files and put them in their proper place, similar to The Sims, Need For Speed, etc.<br>
<br>
Quote: If you go into a server tha uses a module you dont have will it be automatically downloaded and installed correctly or would I still have to manually find/install the mod ???<br>
<br>
For modules, clients do not need the modules installed on their computers to play. No downloading occurs.<br>
<br>
Quote: Mokerr wrote: The bulk of the code is the game itself which you already have installed. So all you would download is the script, a few text files and sound files I would imagine. Probably be similar to CS or UT where the server sends everything you need to you and you just go from there.<br>
<br>
Nothing is downloaded if you the client playing on a NWN server. Information is streamed to the client, but it is not a file that is being sent.<br>
<br>
Quote: Becker wrote: Some of us wackos are making single-player downladable modules. We won't be hosting them. So someone goes to our site, gets the zip file, Unzips it, and then plays. RPG Fanatic wants to know how hard it will be after you do the unzipping in this particular application of your upcoming release.<br>
<br>
Well, we are even trying to make that a one step process, too. I can't comment any more on it right now, but we hope to have something for the solo module authors to make it easier for their users.<br>
<br>
Trent Oster - Producer - NWN<br>
<br>
Morbid Tilesets <br>
Quote: trc wrote: Bleak, desolate areas to include: lifeless forests burned out grasslands ragged rock plains swamps with nothing but dead trees &quot;Scottish highlands&quot; type settings moors lots of variations on rough rocky cliffsides Ruins, ruins, and more ruins and then some more variations on those ruins ...and, especially important, an ability to MIX tilesets in an area (albeit there are graphic implications for blending tiles, mixing mipmaps, etc.)<br>
<br>
The tilesets you suggest are a little morbid, don't you think? What about marsh filled with rotting corpses, hell city tileset with walls built from tormented souls? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  On the mixing tilesets issue, we build tilesets to keep unique texture and geometry counts down so our game doesn't require a 128mb video card and 512 mb of main system memory.<br>
<br>
Gibbed Creatures <br>
Chunks are in. Alex Scott, our local effects artist just re-did my old placeholders and they look good. There are few things in life that can bring as much joy as a freshly chunked Gnome Illusionist. <br>
<br>
Many things at the same time <br>
You can go into an &quot;active search&quot; which slows your movement rate to walking only. Stealth has the same effect with movement rate, forcing your character to walk. If you are in both modes at the same time you are moving at 1/2 walk speed (quite slow). IF you are also encumbered on top of ACtive search and stealth your movement rate will decline further.<br>
<br>
David Gaider - Design, Bioware corp.<br>
<br>
Animal Companions <br>
What exactly were you interested in knowing? Last time I saw they had both animal companions as well as the familiars in. The animal companions are pretty tough. Having a druid or ranger in your party with their dire wolf or mountain lion (or whatever the case might be) is pretty effective. Don't know how much specific information you're going to get at this point, though. How it works is still being tweaked as people are trying it out.<br>
<br>
Quote: I think the question is - to get an animal companion does the Druid have to find the animal in the wild and cast the spell on it (giving her the choice of an animal, but also limiting her to what is avialable) or is the animal &quot;summoned&quot; by the spell?<br>
<br>
Animal companions are summoned.<br>
<br>
Quote: Does she get to chose from a list or is the animal predetermined?<br>
<br>
You get to choose from a list. The animals also level up as you do.<br>
<br>
Quote: And I wanted to know if my Cleric with the Animal domain would get one! I've heard domain powers are out, but I've also heard domain spells will not be exactly the same, so I was hoping Animal Friendship might be a animal domain spell.<br>
<br>
Sorry...don't know about Clerics getting anything with regards to animals or domain spells. I doubt it, as it's meant to be a class feature for the Druids and Rangers, but I could be wrong.<br>
<br>
Quote: BTW, Mr. Gaider, are you on the NWN team?? I thought you oly worked on the BG series, if you're on NWN too... then.... er..... cool!<br>
<br>
Yep, I've been full time again on NWN for a while again, now. <br>
<br>
Druids <br>
If I remember right, I think the scimitars were given to Druids to make them more like the Celtic druids. Or was that the scythe? Do 3rd edition druids use scythes? Hmmm...if not, they probably should. <br>
<br>
Animal companions are a big plus for druids, too, don't forget that. The ability to carry on a coversation with the local fauna that's in-the-know is not to be underestimated, either. <br>
<br>
Simple features <br>
Quote: When you are the boss of a multi-year, megabucks, team project, feel free to decide what is easy to implement, and what is difficult. I'm continually amazed by all the programming experts on these boards. &quot;Why don't they put feature X in? It's so simple, I could do it with one line of code.&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm afraid I have to agree with this one. Domain abilities are perfectly legitimate and no, not incredibly difficult to put in. However, we still may not have time to do it. There are numerous other things related to the rules we simply will not be able to put in the game right now, either...no matter how much we'd like to.<br>
<br>
I think the idea is to get in as much as possible, and make it work and be stable and be fun. Once we've got that accomplished, we can worry about getting in all the details. I don't know what the situation with domain powers is, personally...but somehow I think Clerics will still be quite well-off so long as they get access to their domain spells and auto-substitution of cure/cause spells. Those are, by far, the Cleric's bread and butter.<br>
<br>
Summoned creatures <br>
Let me tell you this. I don't know the exact list of summoned monsters in the game, myself, though I do know the one in the rulebook. And there are two things that come to mind that I think I can re-assure you with.<br>
<br>
1) The people doing the spells are very dogmatic about doing them as closely to the book as the engine will allow.<br>
<br>
2) The list of creatures that the game comes with (and yes, I know there will always be some monsters that you like that won't make it into release) has some, what I thought to be anyway, pretty obscure creatures. A lot of ones that you find on the creature summoning list, especially. I still remember doing a double-take the first time I saw the Lantern Archon.<br>
<br>
Whether all these things make it to final release remains to be seen, but there's a lot there already. As far as Monster Summoning and Summon Nature's Ally go, especially, there's a whole assortment of animals which will supply the normal/dire/celestial slots...not to mention the familiars and animal companions...that already exist.<br>
<br>
Hope that puts your mind at ease.<br>
<br>
Jay Watamaniuk - Community Manager<br>
<br>
Animal Companions <br>
Sorry for the wait folks. Here are some answers to a few of the Animal Companions Qs:<br>
<br>
I was wondering if you could tell me about Animal Companions. When you cast Animal Friendship does it summon an animal for you or do you have to find one to cast it on?<br>
<br>
[] ANSWER: You summon your animal companion. If you had to find an animal it would be module specific instead of game specific. Being at the whim of module designers is bad.<br>
<br>
As we get higher in levels does the companion get better or are we just able to cast the spell on more hit dice worth and end up with ton of creatures?<br>
<br>
[] ANSWER: The animal companion gets better as you go up in levels.<br>
<br>
About those animal companions: when you take possession of them (familiar), will you be able, when taking control of a bird, to fly up and see a farther? Or will the camera just be fixed on one altitude?<br>
<br>
[] ANSWER: Animal companions cannot be possessed, this a special power given to familiars only. <br>
<br>
Brent Knowles - Co-Lead Designer<br>
<br>
In game voice <br>
Quote: Mokerr wrote: If there is no in game voice...Please do this.. Implement Radio text commands like CounterStrike. For those of you who don't know, CS's radio commands work like this. There is a main category which has a hot key and then subcategories with a numbered hot key. When you press x,3 you get a WAV file to play that says &quot;Hold this position&quot;. CS has voice now but most people still use the hotkeys because it's faster and gives clear direction. They take a while to learn but once you do, even in a twitch game like CS they can really aid strategy. <br>
<br>
Yep, we already have those. When you make a character you'll be able to choose a voiceset (which influence the actual verbal component that you hear when you press the hotkeys).<br>
