Point Buy <br>
OK, whoa, hold on. I understand the debate has been raging, but lets all try to keep in in perspective. I am sure that Jay will have something more official to say tomorrow.<br>
<br>
Trent Oster - Producer - NWN<br>
<br>
Tile Modeling Info <br>
NWN tiles (and all the art) are built around base helper objects. These &quot;bases&quot; hold most of the game specific data (animation names, durations, etc). You can have a number of objects linked as children to the base and they will be exported as one model. Each child can have it's own texture, so you don't really need sub-object textures. You can model the grass and road, detach the road faces as a new object and apply a different texture. make the road a child of the grass and you should be just fine (just don't move the road). Tiling works fine as long as the texture can be completely repeated (you can't crop sub sections and repeat them). Basically, the system works quite well after you adopt a certain workflow pattern and it allows us to keep the native data formats quite clean and quite fast.<br>
<br>
Jay Watamaniuk - Community Manager<br>
<br>
Art Q&amp;A <br>
We received a few technical questions that were in Art Director, Marc Holmes, area of expertise. After a bit of back and forth with Brad and Trent to add their own bits and pieces here it is:<br>
<br>
Q) Am I right in assuming each 10mx10m tile is a separate file?<br>
<br>
A) Well, yes and no ? The source file in Max has all the tiles for one tileset but each tile is treated as single model on export. So a Max source file can generate a large number of model files. Getting source files to people that they can base their tiles on is something we are very interested in and we are looking into.<br>
<br>
Q) Does each tile have a dynamic poly's layer in the same file, and are<br>
there any conventions for these meshes. (in case you call them something different I'm talking collision systems)<br>
<br>
A) The collision system is based on a ?walk mesh?. The ?walk mesh? is just a simplified version of the visual mesh, and is made by hand. No special techniques are required.<br>
<br>
Q) There is some kind of bitmap for the UI map right? Is this stored<br>
separately and associated with the tile by naming it the same?<br>
<br>
A) As it stands, there is a kind of index for a tileset called a &quot;set file&quot;. The map icon, which appears in game, is specified per tile in the set file. There is not a 1-1 correlation with tiles and map icons. For instance the 7 types of flat open cobbles in city all associate with 1 map icon.<br>
<br>
Q) How is other information stored in the scene? Within nulls/locators? Or is it done afterwards within the toolset?<br>
<br>
A) Most other things should be done with either material colors on the walk mesh(for sound, visibility and walkability) or with triggers placed in toolset. Triggers are polygon objects as per BG trap triggers for example.<br>
<br>
Q) Do lights get exported with the tile? Do they need to be done in a<br>
special way?<br>
<br>
A) We feature lights that are preset on the tile and can be turned off and on, and set to different colors. You may also place lights by hand, as objects- i.e. torches, candles etc. The sun and moon properties and the ambient color are set by the area properties. Lights are created using our own custom defined in-game light objects within Max.<br>
<br>
Q) Is pathfinding done with nulls/locators at the modeling stage?<br>
<br>
A) Tiles have to follow pathfinding construction rules. Each tile must be made with one of the legal pathfinding templates. After we ship the game we will look into communicating this information.<br>
<br>
Q) How many textures do you tend to use per tile, or do you work it on a filesize quota?<br>
<br>
A) There should be a set memory footprint for each tileset which you cannot exceed. Otherwise you can organize as you wish within the 'pool'<br>
Those are the general answers.<br>
<br>
Many of these questions need specific answers, but we cannot do that just yet. We mainly don't want to be giving out information that may end up having to change for technical reasons. The last thing people want to do is start work and then have their stuff go out of date!<br>
<br>
David Gaider - Design, Bioware corp.<br>
<br>
Druids <br>
So all you really want to know is...<br>
<br>
1) Do we have different musical instruments? (Or any, for that fact.)<br>
2) Can you play them?<br>
3) Is there a Perform skill, and if there is is it available to all classes?<br>
<br>
That about sum it up? Well, of course you all want to know. Duh. Every question seems perfectly legitimate and important to all of you, I'm sure. At any rate, the last post wasn't the answer. I just wanted to make sure I had my bases covered when I went and asked.<br>
<br>
The answers, then:<br>
<br>
1) Do we have different musical instruments? (Or any, for that fact.)<br>
2) Can you play them?<br>
<br>
There's no musical instruments in the way that I think you're asking. There's no animation of using an instrument, at any rate. A regular item could be created that was an instrument, and it could be 'used' to make a variety of effects (and even play music, if the sound file was available). In fact, you could also make a check vs. Perform in the script lead into different effects or sounds.<br>
<br>
Again, though, there's no animation for actually wielding the instrument. That would be nice, but there's no plan for it currently. Bard Song ability is, of course, something else altogether.<br>
<br>
3) Is there a Perform skill, and if there is is it available to all classes?<br>
<br>
Yes. It's available to those classes which have it in-class at regular cost, anyway, and to the others as a cross-class skill.<br>
<br>
Toad Companions <br>
No toads, I'm afraid. <br>
<br>
Fog Control <br>
Quote: 2) Can the color of the fog be changed? And this raises the follow-up question: can it be changed while the module is running or only when the module is created in the toolset?<br>
<br>
The color of the fog is changeable, yes. As to whether or not fog or colors are changeable on the fly...not sure about that, myself. I'd say probably, but I haven't seen the actual commands.<br>
<br>
Quote: 3) I take it fog is something that applies to an entire area. We can't make sections of fog (i.e. volumetric fog) because of the tile-based nature of NWN. Are these presumptions correct?<br>
<br>
Correct.<br>
<br>
Quote: 4) It has been mentioned that when creating a module in the toolset you can specify its Ambient Light, Sun Light, and Moon Light. Can these all be altered independently of eachother while the module is running? If so, does this pose any significant performance hit on machines?<br>
<br>
If there are commands to change the types of light on the fly (you forgot Diffuse Light in that list, btw), then you will be able to change each one, I'm sure. No, it does not cause much of a performance hit. <br>
<br>
Are there enough polys? <br>
I don't think modem speed has as much to do with the polygon count as processor speed does (although a slow connection on a chugging machine certainly wouldn't help matters insofar as playability goes). When we make our final count of the number of players, NPC's and placeable objects that you can have in an area, it's going to have to be playable by a machine with the minimum specs. And we want the game to have as much as content as possible for those min spec machines.<br>
<br>
There is going to be adjustable detail...but you can only take that so far. You can take away grass effects and other cool but performance-hogging things...but you can't reduce the polygon count of models on the fly (at least, as I understand it you can't...I'm not an artist). You can be sure we'll be making all efforts to enhance performance as possible.<br>
<br>
If we were to raise the min spec requirement a la Luclin (and just what is the min spec requirement for World of Warcraft, anyway? I don't think they've announced that, yet), then certainly...I expect a lot more could be done.<br>
<br>
Should we do that? I don't know, personally. Right now the range in processing speeds out there is so wide. Is it reasonable to expect people to upgrade in order to play? There's a can of worms for ya. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Quote: Do you think you could find one thing out for me? (David or Jay) If I add 50% more polys per scene in my mod, will the engine run it? If so i can just have a higher minimum spec for my mod.<br>
<br>
I will go and ask, but I'll tell you this: when we say what the basic limitation is regarding the number of players/NPC's/placeable objects will be in the game, that is primarily an official number. Meaning that if someone meets our min specs and comes to us saying that they're experiencing crashes when they meet those numbers, that's something we need to look into right away.<br>
<br>
Even with Vampire:Redemption's MP capability, the 'maximum' number of players was set at 4...but if your computer had a greater capacity, you could include more. I saw games that have 6 or even 8 players going in them in the brief time I played the game.<br>
<br>
So I expect that if you included models with higher details in your resources, that shouldn't be a problem so long as it meets NWN's other standards. You just have to keep in mind that anyone who's going to play the game has to a) download those resources from you and b) have an equivalent or greater system in order to run it with any degree of playability.<br>
<br>
I may be wrong, though, so I'll go check.<br>
<br>
Monster Tags <br>
If you create a monster, you can put whatever name to it that you like. Putting in a script that changes the name from 'monster' to 'Hutteroid', or whatever, after the players find out what the creature is actually called (setting the appropriate module global), might also be kind of cool, no?<br>
<br>
With 3rd edition, players shouldn't expect too much when encountering even the lowly goblin. If you look at the system, there's a whole big thing in there for the HD-ranges of monsters...never mind using humanoid creatures and adding classes to them. The first time my low-level party encountered a 5th-level Sorcerer kobold and his 4th-level Warrior kobold chieftan they learned to be wary. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
(and, yes...putting these classes on monsters is easy to do, especially with the Creature Wizard.) <br>
<br>
Difficulty Indicator <br>
(Ed. Note: This post is in reference to an indicators used in MMORPG games like Everquest, and Anarchy Online, that would appear over a creature. Green is an easy opponent. Yellow is equal and Red is tough)<br>
<br>
No, there's nothing like that in NWN. If your party of 5th-level characters encounter a huge Black Dragon and decide that they can take him...well, they're always free to roll up new characters, aren't they? <br>
<br>
Placeable Campfires <br>
Yes, actually. I believe a campfire is one of the placeable objects. If not, I'm positive that there's a 'pile of wood' object and a seperate 'small fire' object to place on top of it. If you want to be detailed, you can also spread around some blankets.<br>
<br>
Once placed, these objects are only moveable/destroyable by the GM (unless they aren't marked 'indestructable' and are given HP...then the players or maybe monsters can destroy them, as well).<br>
<br>
Will you talk with us? <br>
No, no...after the game is released, we plan on dropping you all like hot potatoes. We'll have a wall of silence go up like communist Russia. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Seriously, though...while I'm not Bob, I have little doubt that we'll be free to chat about the story and whence it came once the possibility of spoilers is past.<br>
<br>
Jonathan Epp - Quality Assurance<br>
